segments.text: August 22nd, if it don't rain anymore.
Right.
And it's about four to two in the afternoon, and we're talking with William H. Cook.
C-double-O-K-E.
Right.
Okay, and you became editor and publisher of the Rockdale Reporter in 1936, didn't you?
Right, yeah.
And you were born in what year?
Here in Rockville?
No, I was born in Clarendon, up in the Panhandle.
In Clarendon?
I didn't see them in town.
I left there at a very early age, apparently.
My father was
So about how old were you when you came to Rockdale?
So I came, when we came to Rockdale in 1912, I would have been five years old.
I'm not exactly sure how long we lived in Clarendon after I was born.
It was apparently not very long.
And then we moved to Brady and lived there.
And left there in 1912 to come to Rockdale.
So you were five years old?
I was about five, yeah.
Do you remember the mine disaster?
I guess you were about six years old.
Well, you know, I remember it the way a child or a kid remembers things.
in his older age.
I heard a man say once that the older I get, the more I can remember about my boyhood, but I can't remember what happened the day before yesterday.
And I haven't quite reached that stage yet.
Because there's a whole lot of things that I can remember vaguely about my boyhood.
And I do remember the mines.
Did your dad talk about the mines very much?
There was not a great deal of talk about the mines.
You know, they were just there, and it was kind of, I mean, everybody's used to them being there.
They've been there for a long time.
They seem to have been a peripheral sort of thing to Rocky.
Yeah, right.
Would you agree with that?
Right, they were.
And they were way out there, four or five miles or more from town.
I remember more about those old mines from later years after I was in high school and out of high school when we used to go dove hunting, quail hunting, and walk across there.
That was after the mines were gone.
And those old sinkholes and things, you know, we could see evidences of the mines.
I remember that really more than I remember the mines.
I remember that last week myself, haven't you?
Well, that's very important, some important information that we need, because what years would your high school years have covered in post-high school years, exactly?
Yeah, well, let me see, I must have graduated, I was such a smart little devil.
I graduated when I was 16.
I believe that's right.
I graduated in 1922.
Okay, and were the mines shut down by that time, or most of them?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, they were shut down by then.
Just when I was a kid, the mines were out there.
But by 1920s, they weren't operating.
Now, there was the Johnny Boniva mine operated a good while out there after all the rest of them had shut down.
That and the strip mining.
And the strip mining came in, uh-huh.
Johnny Boniva, that Johnny Boniva mine.
I don't know whether Johnny bought that or fell heir to it or what, but I knew him real well.
Well, why don't you tell me something about him?
And he made a pot full of money out of that mine.
It was kind of a one-man operation.
I mean, he ran it, and it was his mine.
And he was a young fellow around here, and...
That mine, I don't remember now, it either sold, either sold it or closed it.
I probably closed it because the demand for lignite coal after the arrival of natural gas became so, so low that, you know, it wasn't, there just wasn't a market for it anymore.
Well, according to the newspaper, it changed hands around 1930 or 31, but John Boniva
maintain its superintendent status.
And what I haven't been able to find yet is when it actually shut down.
Yeah, well, no, I wouldn't be able to tell you that either.
Well, did you ever make any trips to the mine?
Not really, not really.
The only trips I ever made to the mine area was when I was just a small kid riding a donkey.
And as I told you once before,
A lot of us boys on Saturday afternoons and Sundays, we'd get a few nickels and we'd get on our donkeys and ride out there to the commissary.
It seemed like that soda pop and nickel candy out there tasted a whole lot better than what you bought in town.
Probably a long donkey ride out there.
Yeah, but if somebody invited any of us to go down in one of those shafts,
We'd have probably been scared to death.
We'd have run from pride.
I don't think I would have gone down in one of them.
I'm not so sure I'd like to go down in one now.
Myself, I feel the same way.
I'm sort of glad they're all closed up.
But when you did go out there, if you could possibly remember, did you go through the mining camps where the Mexicans lived, or did you skirt around them?
No, we never did really visit in them.
Those mining camps, it was just row after row of houses, little wooden shacks that they lived in.
They all looked just alike.
But no, I don't ever remember.
They were off to the right of the dirt highway that we traveled out there at that time, south of the railroad track.
And I can remember seeing them over there, but I don't know that I ever went over and around those towns.
We went out to the mines and just poked around and played, you know, like kids will do.
Did the Mexican families come to Rockdale that often?
Or was there an interchange of the two areas?
I kind of have an idea.
No, the Mexicans came to Rockdale and traded.
about like the farmers came to Rockdale and traded back in the old days.
They came in wagons and traded on Saturday.
That's about the only day farmers came to town in those days.
Now you notice with highways and automobile, farmers come to town and trade every day, but
At that time, I'm pretty sure that those Mexicans, they came to town once or twice a week, and you know, when they bought groceries, they stocked up on them.
They put it in the big supply from the old-time grocery stores before they had the cash and carry, you know.
And of course, they did an awful lot of their buying.
Their needs, they bought from the commissaries or the company store.
Could you sort of sum up in general terms what the attitude of Rockdale was toward the mines themselves and the Mexicans?
Well, I think the attitude of the Rockdale people towards the mines and the Mexican people was good.
We were proud of having the mines out there.
It meant quite a bit to the town.
You can tell that from reading your paper.
And as far as the Mexicans were concerned, no, they were just some old people out there working in the mines.
And we enjoyed a good relationship with them, and they did with us.
Yes, I don't see the... Civil rights and human rights hadn't been heard of then.
Right.
Yeah, I don't see the conflict...
between the Mexicans and the Anglos that you do between the blacks and the Anglos earlier on.
Yeah, that's right.
And even the Anglos and the whites and the American-Americans or the Chicanos, which somebody said a term had just been invented the last ten years.
All right, I have a feeling it's the few Spanish people, the young people that have gone to college and picked up that term because I found that the...
Other people around here don't use that term.
They use Latin, or they use Spanish, or they use Mexican, which has been educating to me.
But actually, as I remember the minds out there, they were just, I'm not just exactly sure that Rockdale citizens thought about them as being an industry.
They were proud of them.
They meant
good business for the town, and they were good for the town, but they don't think of them as being an industry like we think of Alcoa as being the industry now, or in that fact.
Can you give any reason for that?
Well, if they were just so, they were just so established, they'd been there, and you know, it just, I mean, they were just there, and that was it.
And they just sort of faded away.
And it wasn't until the years after that that small towns became conscious of industry and trying to get industries into the small towns.
In those earlier days, that just wasn't too big a thing.
And I think the people of Rockville took the mines kind of matter-of-factly.
That's the attitude I've been getting.
I think that's right.
We were proud of them.
And they were under control of the Texas Bureau of Mines.
And a man named Bruce Gentry, who lived here in Rockdale, was the chairman of the Texas Bureau of Mines all his life, I guess.
Well, Indian Bullock came in.
And then Bullitt came in after him.
After him, right.
And E.A.
Camp was also a member of the board.
He was a member of the board.
Right, so all three of those men were from Rockville.
The mines had a fairly decent accident record.
It was below the average in the United States.
They really did.
I can remember that one big cave-in after that rainy season, and I can remember that
later, a few years later, of some coal burning under the ground out that side.

You could see for a period of several months, you could see smoke coming up just out of the ground over a long area south of the railroad track out there, but it eventually just smothered itself out, and they did have a low accident rate.
especially considering how crude the equipment was in those days as compared to what, gee, if somebody would start putting in a shaft mine out there in that area now, it'd be a big deal.
It'd be a much different technique.
Oh, yeah.
Well, Mr. Cook, were you familiar with any of the, I don't know what word to use, intrapreneurs or capitalists that randomize, like Sharp or E.B.
Phillips?
I knew, yes, I knew all those men.
They were all businessmen in Rockdale.
And Henry Meyer, H.C. Meyer, was the mayor of Rockdale for years and years and years, and a big, you know, a big Rockdale booster.
And E.B.
Phillips was connected with the same hardware firm that Mr. Meyer was, the old Henny and Meyer store here.
He was also the funeral director.
And the funeral director.
He was in charge of that department of the hardware, furniture, and funeral directing.
It was a big story.
It was the Henney and Meyer firm.
They also had the same sort of a business in New Braunfels, and Henney, H-E-N-N-E, was in New Braunfels then.
Oh, I didn't know that.
And Meyer lived up here, uh-huh.
And they had the same kind of an operation in your Broncos back in those days.
Well, generally, you know, talking about the men that owned the mines and ran the mines, were they local people?
Or were the mines run by outside capital?
No, I think most of those particular mines out there were all local.
And there was a Sparks.
Right.
Do you remember anything about Dr. Sparks?
I just, not really.
I just remember him, and I remember the family, and remember, you know, but that was before I got big enough to be interested in how businesses and mine were run.
One thing I noticed that was kind of odd was that the Mexican people have two basic celebrations at least each year, Cinco de Mayo and the 16th of September.
Cinco de Mayo was the big one.
Was it?
Do you remember any of those?
Did you go to any of them?
I don't think I ever went to one, but I heard an awful lot about them.
And there was publicity in the newspapers about them.
And the Mexicans like to celebrate.
the 5th of May.
That was a big day for them.
Do you know, did it affect Rockdale at all?
Did they come in to buy supplies?
I imagine it probably did.
I don't know, but I expect it affected business to a certain extent prior to the celebration.
They had to get ready for it.
But mostly they kept pretty much to themselves and their celebrations were
They were out there among themselves.
Well, I noticed, looking over 37 years in your newspaper, the last couple weeks, that July 4th has always been a big celebration.
Big celebration here, out at Fair Park.
Would the miners and their families come in for that celebration?
Well, now that, I imagine, started after the mining days.
Yeah, after the mines closed down.
Remembering that the mines closed down in the early to mid-20s, do you know what the miners and their families did after they shut down?
No, I don't.
No, I don't.
But the shutdowns out there were gradual, you know.
One mine, then later on another mine.
And it wasn't just like an industry closing up and leaving town.
I see.
So it was throughout the 20s.
Yeah, right.
Were you familiar with any of the physicians that worked out of the mines at all?
Were any of them your friends?
I probably knew most of those physicians at that time.
There were three, Dr. Wallace, Dr.
Sessions, Dr. Coulter.
I expect they were all
here at that time.
But did they ever talk to you about having to go out there?
No, no.
That's been one hole in the in the story so far.
No, I never did but I'm sure they did and they traveled in horse and buggy at that time.
Of course I guess by the 20s they had their own cars.
I imagine, yeah.
So when was the model he invented?
Okay, so you're asking a historian a question he should be able to answer.
No, I don't even know that myself.
Some of those early 1920 papers, I believe.
Oh, well, it was before then.
I think the first one came to Rockdale about 1915, maybe a little earlier.
Probably so.
And some of the miners themselves had them in the 20s.
They were able to save up enough money to purchase them.
But you would say that after the mines were shut down that the Mexicans would come in for the July 4th celebrations?
I'm sure they did.
I noticed you had county fairs quite often.
The county fair in Rockdale way back in the early days was an enormous
a celebration.
They had big fairs on there at that time, which was before the July 4th celebration.
Actually, the July 4th celebration probably came into being after World War I, and most of them were sponsored by the American Legion.
And every year they got just a little bit bigger.
But prior to that, quite a few years prior to that,
was when the old Rockdale Fair was in all its glory.
The streets weren't paved here, they were dirt streets.
And they had parades with floats, you know, on wagons drawn by teams of horses and mules.
I remember reading descriptions of that.
Yeah, and they were big events, I tell you.
Daredevil airplane riders.
I remember that.
I remember when one crashed out there when I was a kid.
Yeah, they were quite disappointed when that happened.
They didn't get to see the air show.
Right.
They were more concerned about that than they were.
than he was a pilot of that plane, I think, although I don't believe he was hurt critically.
No, but he did refuse to go back up again.
He enjoyed about as much of that as he could stand for the day, I think.
What do you think, do you think Lignite is finally going to make a bigger impact on Rockville?
Oh yes, no doubt about that.
What would you attribute that to?
Well, every year now,
the demand for energy has been showing up more and more, and lignite's becoming more and more prominent now.
And Alcoa has been generating their own electricity out there with lignite fuel ever since 1952.
And that's because lignite was out there is the reason Alcoa is here.
And there
right now, building this addition to the power plant, which was more than double its size.
And that will...
They've got a three-unit power plant they built in 1952.
I remember writing publicity about that at the time, and we had pictures of it, and they said it was large enough to furnish
It confers enough power for six cities the size of Austin at the time it was put into production out there.
Well, since then, Austin has grown quite some.
And also, the aluminum smelter has more than doubled in its production and size.
And the demand for electricity and power has just gone up and up and up.
Of course, out there they used a strip mining technique, whereas the early lignite mining was shaft.
Yeah, that's the early lignite mining was shaft mining.
Well, I'm wondering what the economic difference is.
I mean, back in the early days, you did have Mexicans coming into town to buy clothes and nothing else.
So you did have, you know, money coming in.
Right, but that was the number of Mexicans working in the mines.
was just insignificant as compared to the number of people working out here, even just in the mines, in the strip mining.
There's more people working in the strip mine now than there were?
Yeah.
It's a far bigger operation than all the old shaft mines put together.
I see.
So technology came in with the big strip mining shovels, but it also brought more jobs.
And with the addition of this power plant now, they're increasing.
TP&L and Alcoa are building this new power unit as a cooperative venture.
They're both involved in it.
And of course Shell is here too.
Yeah, but of course they're a separate identity.
They're on their own.
They're coming in and making plans to start a new strip mine operation.
And they don't know just what they're going to do with that lignite that they mined yet, but they're hoping to find what they call a mine mouth customer.
And I think that will mean quite a bit to this area.
Well, do you think the nature of Rockvale is going to change with Alcoa expanding and Shell coming in here?
We will remain pretty much the same.
We'll grow.
I think we're in for some real growth.
I think I don't believe the future ever looked any better for Rockdale and does right now.
Well, do you think you'll lose some of the rural town flavor?
I noticed the other day at 5 o'clock it took me two or three lights to get through.
And I just had the feeling that that was an unusual...
thing at least 10 or 20 years ago.
Oh yeah, there weren't any traffic lights in those days, but the streets were terrible.
So with the bad you get the good.
Yeah, that's right.
Because Rockdale will grow and I think our business district will grow.
When Alcor came in in 1951, from that time until now,
When they came in, our population was just a little over 2,000.
And now it's, I would guess, a conservative estimate would be between 6,000 and 7,000.
But our business district hasn't grown in proportion to the population.
I think with the new development in the next six or eight, ten years now, there will be more business growth.
You said Brown and Root is also in the area now?
Well, they're building, they've got the contract to build that fire plant for TPNL and Alcoa.
I see.
First of all, they'll come in and then they'll leave, right?
Yeah, right.
Their target date for completion of that plant is 1981.
So they'll be here until.
Well, what kind of a shock will that be to Rockville once they leave?
When the Alcoa construction was over in 1951, we went through pretty much the same thing, you know.
A big industry hit a small town all of a sudden, and the impact was terrific.
And, you know, we had hundreds and hundreds of construction workers in here for several years.
We'd have several, I think, construction workers on this brown roof project.

will peak at about 500 but as the plant gets into operation the mining activities will increase and there'll be more employment there to take up some of that slack and about that same time Shell has plans for starting its strip mining operations which which will just be getting started when when this quits so for another period of another three to five years they will
There'll be some construction activity followed by new industrial and mining activity.
That's the way it looks to me right now.
Well, if we jump back in history just a little bit, I'm trying to see if there are any parallels.
Maybe there is, maybe there isn't.
And I realize that you would have only been about eight years old, or even younger.
Between 1910 and 1920, for instance, generally in Texas there was a great migration of Mexican workers to Texas because of the Revolution.
Do you remember any sort of impact that had on Rockdale?
Not really, no.
No, I really don't.
Because from all the time we had a lot of Mexicans working in the mining area out there.
And I suspect that after the mines closed and the Americans, I think just like the old fellow Morales you're talking about, he moved to town.
So most of them, when the mines shut down, they did move?
And a lot of them, I think, moved in town and got jobs, or they went out on a farm and farmed, or maybe they left somewhere else.
But they were just kind of absorbed in the flow, the ebb and flow.
There wasn't any pressure then on Rockdale's charity organizations to take care of them?
No, no.
That's unusual.
Well, it would be today.
In those days, it wasn't.
Well, one thing I've noticed, Mr. Cook, is that
Up north, they had company town situations, you know, the old Coleman car company town.
And the situation here in Rockdale seems much more progressive than that town.
I mean, here in Rockdale, they paid cash.
The Mexicans could move around from mine to mine.
And up north, they were paid in company script.
They could not go into town to buy other things.
Do you have any idea why people like Sharp and Sessions and Phillips developed a system like that?
No, I don't.
I think, I don't, I have an idea that it wasn't done intentionally.
I think it just, I think it just happened.
I think it's just one of those things that happened.
Well, I wonder if Mr. Vogel, you know, Herman Vogel had anything to do with that.
Well, he had, he bound to have had something to...
to do with it, but he was one of the mine owners.
That's something I'd like to be able to explain, you know, why it was a much more free-flowing, more progressive situation.
Well, I really hadn't thought about it.
I can see what you mean.
Well, the fascinating thing is, as we said earlier, it was a peripheral sort of industry.
And Rockdale is agriculturally oriented more.
It was then more than it is now.
There's very little agriculture there now.
But you know, those mines, those Mexicans came in here gradually as the mines opened up.
It wasn't like a big industry setting down like Alco did in 51.
A mine opened here.
A year or two later, a mine opened there.
It was a gradual process, and then they closed the same way.
And there wasn't any big influx or big outgo of that Mexican population at any time, I don't believe.
But it was, do you think it was fairly fluid?
I mean, you know, new people came in, and the people that were here left, or was it a sort of an internal growth, sort of?
I think it was more of a kind of an internal growth than a family affair growth.
You know, like the fellow Morales, he worked in the mines as a youth.
His father worked in the mines, I feel sure, maybe his grandfather.
and you know they they grew up these American miners their families grew the boys grew into the mine.
Well I sure didn't want to thank you for your time can you think of anything else?
I really no I really can't I wish I could.
If you happen to run into you know an answer or a personal answer to why the Rockdale Ignite mine situation was more progressive you know I'd appreciate
Well, I'll tell you one possible reason.
